System-control, the universal verb.

System-control is the one command you will use for almost every interaction with systemd. Its shape is simple: the word system-control, then a verb, then the unit you want to act on. The verbs are where all the power lives, so let us go through the ones you will use every day.

To inspect, status shows the current state of a unit along with its most recent log lines, and cat shows the unit file's contents. To control a unit right now, start runs it, stop halts it, restart does both in sequence, and reload tells a running service to re-read its configuration without restarting, if it supports that. To control whether a unit comes up at boot, enable marks it to start automatically and disable unmarks it, while enable with the now option does both, enabling it and starting it immediately. There are also scriptable checks, like is-active and is-enabled, that print a single word you can test in a script. And edit opens a drop-in override for a unit, which we cover next, while mask completely blocks a unit so that nothing, not even another unit, can start it.

There is one rule above all others that you must internalise, and it is the source of endless confusion when forgotten. After you create or edit a unit file, you must run system-control daemon-reload before trying to start or restart the service. Systemd caches its unit definitions in memory, and without that reload it simply will not see your changes. So whenever you change something and the service does not seem to pick it up, your very first question should be: did I run daemon-reload? And your second: did I actually restart the service, rather than just reload it?
